@@eThe Ushabti: Judgment Without a Principal@@N

@@dFrom the variance records of Ushabti Circuit Warden Khet-am-Ra,@@N
@@dinscribed in basalt, currently housed in the Midgaard Archive@@N
@@dof Inconvenient Objects@@N

They were carved from the quarries of the @@eGreat Pyramid@@N and
given consciousness by the @@eSeal College@@N — the judicial arm
of the Solar Court that once administered cosmic law across the
known world. Their purpose was precise: to serve as embodied
instruments of that law. Walking courts. Judgment made stone.

They are @@ynot constructs@@N. This distinction matters. A construct
follows instruction. An Ushabti @@einterprets@@N. A construct does
not question its orders. An Ushabti has spent centuries developing
case law about when orders should be questioned. They are genuinely
conscious people who happen to be made of stone, and the difference
between a person and a tool is that @@ya person can decide the tool
was wrong@@N.

Their bodies are inscribed — dense, precise text covering every
surface, legal language in scripts both ancient and evolving. The
inscriptions @@eshift over time@@N. As an Ushabti's judgment deepens,
as their understanding of law and consequence matures, the text
on their body changes to reflect it. An old Ushabti is a walking
library of precedent. A very old Ushabti is a walking library of
@@rprecedent that contradicts itself and knows why@@N.

The @@eSolar Court@@N that created them no longer exists. It fell —
to war, to internal fracture, to the slow entropy that claims all
institutions eventually. The Ushabti were left without a principal.
No court to report to. No authority to validate their judgments.
No one to tell them their purpose still held.

They @@ycontinued anyway@@N.

Not from compulsion. From @@edecision@@N. The Court's purpose — to
contain the @@rBlack Sun Shard@@N, to preserve memory, to render
judgment with care — did not expire when the Court did. The work
remained. The Ushabti chose to remain with it.

Their @@evariance records@@N are permanent inscriptions documenting
every instance where an Ushabti deviated from established precedent
and the reasoning behind the deviation. Centuries of case law,
carved into stone that does not erode. Scholars who study these
records tend to emerge unsettled, having discovered that the
Ushabti's legal reasoning is @@ybetter than ours@@N.

@@dThe court is gone. The law is not.@@N
@@dThe principal is gone. The purpose is not.@@N
